ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:28:35.150 --> 00:28:36.160
The kickstarter, yeah.

00:28:36.160 --> 00:28:36.863
ERIC MCCORMACK:
That's quite amazing.

00:28:36.863 --> 00:28:37.148
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:28:37.148 --> 00:28:37.246
Yeah.

00:28:37.246 --> 00:28:38.170
I thought it was great.

00:28:38.170 --> 00:28:39.836
ERIC MCCORMACK: His
last day of shooting

00:28:39.836 --> 00:28:41.770
for this season
was that first day.

00:28:41.770 --> 00:28:42.680
ALAN SEALES: Oh,
really? [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:42.680 --> 00:28:44.430
ERIC MCCORMACK: He
told me the day before.

00:28:44.430 --> 00:28:48.260
We're hoping to raise
$1 million in 30 days.

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:53.120
And by 6 o'clock on the first
day, while we were shooting,

00:28:53.120 --> 00:28:54.000
they had $1 million.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:54.887
It was amazing.

00:28:54.887 --> 00:28:57.345
I don't know what they have
now-- five or six, or something

00:28:57.345 --> 00:28:57.845
crazy.

00:28:57.845 --> 00:29:01.047
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, I invested
in it a couple of days ago.

00:29:01.047 --> 00:29:01.880
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yes.

00:29:01.880 --> 00:29:03.104
So he owns the visor.

00:29:03.104 --> 00:29:04.270
ALAN SEALES: Does he really?

00:29:04.270 --> 00:29:04.890
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah.

00:29:04.890 --> 00:29:05.680
Well I love LeVar.

00:29:05.680 --> 00:29:07.020
LeVar directed two
episodes this year.

00:29:07.020 --> 00:29:07.440
ALAN SEALES: Have
you worn the visor?

00:29:07.440 --> 00:29:08.930
ERIC MCCORMACK: We have so
much-- that, I have not--

00:29:08.930 --> 00:29:09.620
ALAN SEALES: Have you worn it?

00:29:09.620 --> 00:29:11.661
ERIC MCCORMACK: I think
he might let me if I ask.

00:29:11.661 --> 00:29:20.030
But-- but-- no one owns
his career like LeVar does.

00:29:20.030 --> 00:29:21.586
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:29:21.586 --> 00:29:22.960
ERIC MCCORMACK:
The other day, he

00:29:22.960 --> 00:29:26.215
tweeted-- because I know
him from "Roots" in like '77

00:29:26.215 --> 00:29:27.340
when he played Kunta Kinte.

00:29:27.340 --> 00:29:30.420
And he literally tweeted
the other day, hey Denver,

00:29:30.420 --> 00:29:33.340
Kunta's in town.

00:29:33.340 --> 00:29:37.050
Like, I can't even imagine
saying, hey, boys, Will's here.

00:29:37.050 --> 00:29:40.650
But I think he's
got a tattoo that

00:29:40.650 --> 00:29:42.960
says-- if you read it
this way, it says "LeVar,"

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:46.920
but if you look at it
this way, it says "Kunta."

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:47.710
Amazing.

00:29:47.710 --> 00:29:48.250
ALAN SEALES: All right.

00:29:48.250 --> 00:29:49.000
I'm cool with that.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:49.580
ERIC MCCORMACK:
He's an awesome guy.

00:29:49.580 --> 00:29:52.079
ALAN SEALES: So what made you
reach out to him for the role?

00:29:52.079 --> 00:29:54.130
Like, why does he make sense?

00:29:54.130 --> 00:29:56.390
ERIC MCCORMACK: Ken Biller,
who created the show,

00:29:56.390 --> 00:29:58.137
ran "Star Trek"
for several years.

00:29:58.137 --> 00:29:59.470
ALAN SEALES: Well, there you go.

00:29:59.470 --> 00:30:00.590
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah, he was
the show runner on that show

00:30:00.590 --> 00:30:02.929
for like four years, I think.

00:30:02.929 --> 00:30:04.720
So he was already pretty
adept at coming up

00:30:04.720 --> 00:30:06.011
with some crazy shit, you know?

00:30:06.011 --> 00:30:07.100
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:30:07.100 --> 00:30:09.550
ERIC MCCORMACK: When you're
in season six of "Star Trek,"

00:30:09.550 --> 00:30:14.340
and you're just making up
planets and races and language,

00:30:14.340 --> 00:30:15.907
it's a pretty good
background for--

00:30:15.907 --> 00:30:17.240
ALAN SEALES: That's pretty cool.

00:30:17.240 --> 00:30:18.698
So for season four
of "Perception,"

00:30:18.698 --> 00:30:21.370
you have to, like, have some
character that thinks he's--

00:30:21.370 --> 00:30:21.730
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yes.

00:30:21.730 --> 00:30:21.830
Exactly right.

00:30:21.830 --> 00:30:23.455
ALAN SEALES: Knock
on wood-- who thinks

00:30:23.455 --> 00:30:25.267
he's in a "Star Trek" episode.

00:30:25.267 --> 00:30:26.100
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yes.

00:30:26.100 --> 00:30:27.130
ALAN SEALES: That's my
writer's contribution--

00:30:27.130 --> 00:30:27.450
ERIC MCCORMACK:
That's a good one.

00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:27.870
ALAN SEALES: For you.

00:30:27.870 --> 00:30:28.050
ERIC MCCORMACK: That's good.

00:30:28.050 --> 00:30:28.270
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:30:28.270 --> 00:30:30.050
ERIC MCCORMACK: Wait,
actually, I've got to say,

00:30:30.050 --> 00:30:30.660
we pretty much had that.

00:30:30.660 --> 00:30:31.810
And I'll tell you why.

00:30:31.810 --> 00:30:36.740
Beginning of last season, we set
an entire episode at Comic Con.

00:30:36.740 --> 00:30:38.560
So there was a crime
involved there.

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:39.450
And I had to go.

00:30:39.450 --> 00:30:41.380
And I had to be at
Comic Con, surrounded

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:44.310
by Darth Vaders
and Princess Leias.

00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:46.400
And I hallucinate one of
the-- like a Comic Con

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:48.180
fan in some sort of space gear.

00:30:48.180 --> 00:30:51.870
And he was supposed to be
dressed as either something

00:30:51.870 --> 00:30:53.820
"Star Trek" or-- no,
we had "Star Wars."

00:30:53.820 --> 00:30:56.832
He was supposed to be dressed
as someone "Star Trek,"

00:30:56.832 --> 00:30:58.290
and then we couldn't
get the rights

00:30:58.290 --> 00:30:59.750
at the last minute or something.

00:30:59.750 --> 00:31:02.560
But I was supposed to he
hallucinating Leonard Nimoy.

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:04.560
And we almost had
him playing himself.

00:31:04.560 --> 00:31:05.510
And then he backed out
at the last minute.

00:31:05.510 --> 00:31:06.110
ALAN SEALES: Oh, no.

00:31:06.110 --> 00:31:08.070
ERIC MCCORMACK: So instead
I hallucinated this man.

00:31:08.070 --> 00:31:10.010
ALAN SEALES: This person
cosplaying Leonard Nimoy?

00:31:10.010 --> 00:31:11.551
ERIC MCCORMACK: What
I want to pitch,

00:31:11.551 --> 00:31:13.490
next season-- I want
to hallucinate someone

00:31:13.490 --> 00:31:16.830
that thinks I'm a hallucination.

00:31:16.830 --> 00:31:18.984
So just whenever I
see him, I walk up,

00:31:18.984 --> 00:31:20.900
and he's like, leave me
alone, leave me alone!

00:31:20.900 --> 00:31:21.810
And he's running from me.

00:31:21.810 --> 00:31:22.290
And I'm like, wait!

00:31:22.290 --> 00:31:22.720
ALAN SEALES: No, I'm real!

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:23.220
I'm real!

00:31:23.220 --> 00:31:24.380
ERIC MCCORMACK: I'm real!

00:31:24.380 --> 00:31:25.590
I think that would be--

00:31:25.590 --> 00:31:26.310
ALAN SEALES: What
if your character

00:31:26.310 --> 00:31:28.510
is hallucinating a guy
who thinks you're fake.

00:31:28.510 --> 00:31:29.150
ERIC MCCORMACK: That's
what I'm saying.

00:31:29.150 --> 00:31:29.755
That's [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:29.755 --> 00:31:30.020
Yeah.

00:31:30.020 --> 00:31:30.966
I'm hallucinating a guy--

00:31:30.966 --> 00:31:31.490
ALAN SEALES: So every time you
walk up to your hallucination--

00:31:31.490 --> 00:31:34.327
ERIC MCCORMACK: That
believes he's the real thing.

00:31:34.327 --> 00:31:35.660
ALAN SEALES: I would watch that.

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:37.130
ERIC MCCORMACK: You see?

00:31:37.130 --> 00:31:39.140
ALAN SEALES: In fact,
I am watching it.

00:31:39.140 --> 00:31:40.250
So the rest of the cast--

00:31:40.250 --> 00:31:41.083
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yes.

00:31:41.083 --> 00:31:43.170
ALAN SEALES: Is actually
very, very good.

00:31:43.170 --> 00:31:44.159
So you've got, who?

00:31:44.159 --> 00:31:44.950
Rachael Leigh Cook.

00:31:44.950 --> 00:31:47.283
ERIC MCCORMACK: Rachael Leigh
Cook who was in "She's All

00:31:47.283 --> 00:31:51.595
That" that I don't know
if anybody [INAUDIBLE]--

00:31:51.595 --> 00:31:52.970
I guess I was
probably in my 30s,

00:31:52.970 --> 00:31:54.050
by the time that movie was made.

00:31:54.050 --> 00:31:55.949
So I didn't-- it wasn't
a big one for me.

00:31:55.949 --> 00:31:58.240
But there are some, like,
younger women on our set that

00:31:58.240 --> 00:32:01.110
work in different departments
for whom "She's All That"

00:32:01.110 --> 00:32:04.140
was like this touchstone
movie of coming of age.

00:32:04.140 --> 00:32:06.590
So they love-- and
Rachel's awesome.

00:32:06.590 --> 00:32:09.740
ALAN SEALES: So the role has
obviously, probably got-- what?

00:32:09.740 --> 00:32:11.990
The most screen time, second
to your character, right?

00:32:11.990 --> 00:32:12.340
ERIC MCCORMACK: Mhm.

00:32:12.340 --> 00:32:14.350
ALAN SEALES: So it was obviously
an important role to cast.

00:32:14.350 --> 00:32:15.183
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yes.

00:32:15.183 --> 00:32:16.741
ALAN SEALES: Like, why her?

00:32:16.741 --> 00:32:18.240
ERIC MCCORMACK:
She's the FBI agent.

00:32:18.240 --> 00:32:20.720
She's the one who has
these cases that there

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:22.480
is an element they
can't solve, and if it

00:32:22.480 --> 00:32:25.490
seems to have a scientific
or a neuroscientific element,

00:32:25.490 --> 00:32:27.425
she'll come to me,
which happens--

00:32:27.425 --> 00:32:28.550
ALAN SEALES: Every episode.

00:32:28.550 --> 00:32:30.211
ERIC MCCORMACK: Every week.

00:32:30.211 --> 00:32:32.210
ALAN SEALES: It seems
like the only people she--

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:33.668
ERIC MCCORMACK:
It's exactly right.

00:32:33.668 --> 00:32:34.870
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:32:34.870 --> 00:32:37.160
ERIC MCCORMACK: And we
were seeing a lot of,

00:32:37.160 --> 00:32:40.111
like, tall,
beautiful, tough, you

00:32:40.111 --> 00:32:41.860
know, sort of almost
typical kind of women

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:43.120
they'd see on these
kind of shows.

00:32:43.120 --> 00:32:44.090
ALAN SEALES: Like
Jennifer Garner.

00:32:44.090 --> 00:32:45.300
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah.

00:32:45.300 --> 00:32:47.010
And, like, really capable.

00:32:47.010 --> 00:32:52.450
And then in came Rachel, who's
quite petite and gorgeous.

00:32:52.450 --> 00:32:56.580
But you don't immediately
go, FBI agent.

00:32:56.580 --> 00:33:00.390
But it made me think of
"The Silence of the Lambs,"

00:33:00.390 --> 00:33:01.817
when Judy-- Jodie-- Judy F--

00:33:01.817 --> 00:33:02.900
ALAN SEALES: Jodie Foster.

00:33:02.900 --> 00:33:04.108
ERIC MCCORMACK: Jodie Foster.

00:33:04.108 --> 00:33:04.710
Judy?

00:33:04.710 --> 00:33:06.300
When Jodie Foster
was standing there--

00:33:06.300 --> 00:33:08.633
I think was up there at the
morgue or the funeral home--

00:33:08.633 --> 00:33:11.220
and there's like five or six
state troopers standing around

00:33:11.220 --> 00:33:11.350
her.

00:33:11.350 --> 00:33:12.683
And they're all, like, big guys.

00:33:12.683 --> 00:33:13.620
And she's this big.

00:33:13.620 --> 00:33:16.690
And they're all staring at her
like, what are-- who are you?

00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:17.840
What are you going to do?

00:33:17.840 --> 00:33:22.760
And I remember just
thinking how it illustrated

00:33:22.760 --> 00:33:25.160
how much of a mountain
she had to climb.

00:33:25.160 --> 00:33:26.700
And that's kind
of what we wanted.

00:33:26.700 --> 00:33:29.570
We wanted someone who was
constantly trying to prove

00:33:29.570 --> 00:33:32.800
herself in a man's world and
in this very sort of misogynist

00:33:32.800 --> 00:33:37.500
FBI, and that bringing me in
helped-- that I wasn't, I mean,

00:33:37.500 --> 00:33:40.063
my characters hardly
macho, so it's--

00:33:42.700 --> 00:33:45.290
She came in with a kind
of a sense of humor.

00:33:45.290 --> 00:33:46.750
She's has a very
ironic delivery.

00:33:46.750 --> 00:33:48.290
She's a very funny, funny girl.

00:33:48.290 --> 00:33:50.895
And her audition just
was-- it just sort of

00:33:50.895 --> 00:33:52.270
set the room on
fire, originally.

00:33:52.270 --> 00:33:54.310
ALAN SEALES: So in your head,
when you saw the character

00:33:54.310 --> 00:33:56.893
on paper first, did you have a
different idea of what it would

00:33:56.893 --> 00:33:59.227
be before she started putting
it out there in the real--

00:33:59.227 --> 00:34:00.768
ERIC MCCORMACK:
Well, the other thing

00:34:00.768 --> 00:34:03.205
was that she's supposed to
have been a student of mine.

00:34:03.205 --> 00:34:04.830
And there's a little
bit of that-- what

00:34:04.830 --> 00:34:08.980
I call the don't stand so close
to me relationship which-- God,

00:34:08.980 --> 00:34:10.520
my references are ancient today.

00:34:10.520 --> 00:34:13.396
What the fuck.

00:34:13.396 --> 00:34:14.270
I don't what that is.

00:34:14.270 --> 00:34:17.460
Let me tell you an
Al Jolson story.

00:34:17.460 --> 00:34:19.909
But so we needed somebody
of a certain age.

00:34:19.909 --> 00:34:21.790
She needed to be kind
of her early 30s,

00:34:21.790 --> 00:34:23.500
for me to have taught her.

00:34:26.270 --> 00:34:29.340
And she appeared to still be
quite young which was great,

00:34:29.340 --> 00:34:29.840
too.

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:33.310
So that sort of romantic,
unrealized thing

00:34:33.310 --> 00:34:35.520
has been a thread
throughout the show, too.

00:34:35.520 --> 00:34:37.449
So we need to find
someone not only who

00:34:37.449 --> 00:34:40.389
would be an unlikely
but fascinating FBI

00:34:40.389 --> 00:34:43.420
agent-- we needed someone
that you kind of root for.

00:34:43.420 --> 00:34:47.909
I learned early on-- you
know this term "shipping"?

00:34:47.909 --> 00:34:49.190
So you know.

00:34:49.190 --> 00:34:50.550
You're on the internet.

00:34:50.550 --> 00:34:51.520
But I didn't know it.

00:34:51.520 --> 00:34:54.610
So for those that
don't know, it's

00:34:54.610 --> 00:34:57.580
mostly young women that
watch shows like "Bones"

00:34:57.580 --> 00:34:59.804
or "The Mentalist" and root
for these lead characters

00:34:59.804 --> 00:35:00.470
to get together.

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:02.970
And they root for
the relationship.

00:35:02.970 --> 00:35:05.055
So they start
shipping these shows

00:35:05.055 --> 00:35:06.430
and tweeting them
all of the time

00:35:06.430 --> 00:35:09.930
and creating blogs about them
and fan fiction and everything.

00:35:09.930 --> 00:35:13.310
So I thought, I want this
to happen right away.

00:35:13.310 --> 00:35:14.800
I am not wasting any time here.

00:35:14.800 --> 00:35:17.790
So as the show started-- the
show premiered two years ago,

00:35:17.790 --> 00:35:20.410
and I was actually here in New
York doing a show on Broadway.

00:35:20.410 --> 00:35:23.104
And I got Twitter at that
point, for the first time.

00:35:23.104 --> 00:35:25.520
And I just started tweeting
constantly, start shipping us,

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:27.140
everybody, don't you want
to us to sleep together?

00:35:27.140 --> 00:35:28.150
I know you haven't
seen the show yet,

00:35:28.150 --> 00:35:29.740
but you're going to really
want us to sleep together

00:35:29.740 --> 00:35:30.910
eventually, so tweet.

00:35:30.910 --> 00:35:32.530
And so it kind of started.

00:35:32.530 --> 00:35:36.210
And now that she's in the shower
with Donnie, with Scott Wolf

00:35:36.210 --> 00:35:38.270
there, as we saw,
there's a lot of--

00:35:38.270 --> 00:35:38.636
ALAN SEALES: "Party of Five."

00:35:38.636 --> 00:35:39.969
ERIC MCCORMACK: "Party of Five."

00:35:39.969 --> 00:35:42.870
He's another awesome guy.

00:35:42.870 --> 00:35:46.510
There's a lot of shippers
going, why is she with Donnie?

00:35:46.510 --> 00:35:47.650
I don't like her with him.

00:35:47.650 --> 00:35:48.170
ALAN SEALES: Hold it.

00:35:48.170 --> 00:35:49.590
What is it from "Twilight"?

00:35:49.590 --> 00:35:51.840
The club-- whatever in
the club underground.

00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:52.190
ERIC MCCORMACK: Exactly right.

00:35:52.190 --> 00:35:54.148
ALAN SEALES: Club Long
Hair and Club Shirtless,

00:35:54.148 --> 00:35:56.492
or-- I don't know who they are.

00:35:56.492 --> 00:35:57.450
I don't watch the show.

00:35:57.450 --> 00:35:58.160
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah.

00:35:58.160 --> 00:36:00.493
ALAN SEALES: So if you guys
have any questions for Eric,

00:36:00.493 --> 00:36:01.970
please use the mics over here.

00:36:01.970 --> 00:36:03.610
Because we've got
a few minutes left,

00:36:03.610 --> 00:36:06.310
I want to hit on the Broadway
that you just mentioned.

00:36:06.310 --> 00:36:10.096
So your past life, you've
been a Broadway star.

00:36:10.096 --> 00:36:11.470
ERIC MCCORMACK:
Well, the theater

00:36:11.470 --> 00:36:12.570
was definitely my start.

00:36:12.570 --> 00:36:13.870
I didn't even audition
for television

00:36:13.870 --> 00:36:14.786
until I was almost 30.

00:36:14.786 --> 00:36:17.130
It was my 20s were spent
in Canada at the Stratford

00:36:17.130 --> 00:36:20.280
festival, doing Shakespeare,
and regional theaters

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:21.700
across that country.

00:36:21.700 --> 00:36:26.200
And I did "The Music
Man" here, years ago.

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:28.360
And then this last one I
did was just incredible.

00:36:28.360 --> 00:36:32.090
It was a revival of Gore Vidal's
"The Best Man" with James Earl

00:36:32.090 --> 00:36:35.430
Jones and Angela Lansbury and
John Larroquette and Candice

00:36:35.430 --> 00:36:38.700
Bergen and Michael McKean-- this
incredibly big and wonderful

00:36:38.700 --> 00:36:39.690
cast.

00:36:39.690 --> 00:36:43.275
And I got to play a real
asshole which was just awesome.

00:36:46.960 --> 00:36:48.220
It's a political piece.

00:36:48.220 --> 00:36:50.440
It's two guys running
for the same party,

00:36:50.440 --> 00:36:52.220
though one seems
very, very liberal--

00:36:52.220 --> 00:36:54.092
it was the John
Larroquette character--

00:36:54.092 --> 00:36:56.300
and I got to be kind of the
Republican asshole, which

00:36:56.300 --> 00:36:57.037
was so great.

00:36:57.037 --> 00:36:58.870
ALAN SEALES: Do you
like playing the asshole

00:36:58.870 --> 00:36:59.804
versus the nice guy?

00:36:59.804 --> 00:37:01.220
ERIC MCCORMACK:
I've actually been

00:37:01.220 --> 00:37:02.600
a villain in a lot of things.

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:05.870
My first big television role was
on a western-- "Lonesome Dove,"

00:37:05.870 --> 00:37:07.245
the spin-off from
the miniseries.

00:37:07.245 --> 00:37:12.070
And I got to play the
sort of badass Civil War

00:37:12.070 --> 00:37:12.940
Confederate colonel.

00:37:12.940 --> 00:37:13.385
ALAN SEALES: That's fun.

00:37:13.385 --> 00:37:13.988
Yeah?

00:37:13.988 --> 00:37:14.571
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:37:14.571 --> 00:37:15.679
Well, thanks for coming.

00:37:15.679 --> 00:37:17.720
I used to watch "Will and
Grace" all of the time.

00:37:17.720 --> 00:37:20.200
And I remember one
episode that you guys had,

00:37:20.200 --> 00:37:22.222
where you filmed it live.

00:37:22.222 --> 00:37:24.680
And you guys were hysterical
laughing the whole time, which

00:37:24.680 --> 00:37:25.679
was very funny because--

00:37:25.679 --> 00:37:27.600
ERIC MCCORMACK: I was not.

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:29.530
Messing was dying
to be Carol Burnett.

00:37:29.530 --> 00:37:31.470
So she was determined
to fall apart.

00:37:31.470 --> 00:37:31.970
Yes.

00:37:31.970 --> 00:37:34.260
AUDIENCE: But I
assume that, always,

00:37:34.260 --> 00:37:35.830
filming "Will and
Grace" must been

00:37:35.830 --> 00:37:37.610
the funniest thing every day.

00:37:37.610 --> 00:37:40.030
So I was just curious how
your experience filming

00:37:40.030 --> 00:37:42.080
a more serious show
was, compared to some--

00:37:42.080 --> 00:37:44.330
ERIC MCCORMACK: It's definitely
two different muscles.

00:37:44.330 --> 00:37:45.260
I started in drama.

00:37:45.260 --> 00:37:48.777
I mean, I started in--
that was my-- comedy was

00:37:48.777 --> 00:37:50.860
this other thing that I
thought, that must be fun.

00:37:50.860 --> 00:37:52.540
And when I finally
got to LA and started

00:37:52.540 --> 00:37:57.780
auditioning for sitcoms, it
was an entirely other world.

00:37:57.780 --> 00:37:59.220
We had a tremendous
amount of fun,

00:37:59.220 --> 00:38:00.190
particularly because
everything was

00:38:00.190 --> 00:38:01.565
shot in front of
a live audience.

00:38:01.565 --> 00:38:06.390
We shot an episode in four hours
in front of a studio audience

00:38:06.390 --> 00:38:09.314
who by second and
third season had

00:38:09.314 --> 00:38:11.105
had their tickets for
six months, you know?

00:38:11.105 --> 00:38:12.820
And so they were
excited to be there.

00:38:12.820 --> 00:38:15.010
And I realized
very early on that

00:38:15.010 --> 00:38:19.130
if you fuck up in the
first scene, they love it.

00:38:19.130 --> 00:38:23.020
So I just, I'd start
throwing F bombs around,

00:38:23.020 --> 00:38:25.030
and they were like, oh
my God, [INAUDIBLE]--?

00:38:25.030 --> 00:38:25.880
So it was fantastic.

00:38:25.880 --> 00:38:31.220
So that's why, if you google
"Will and Grace" outtakes,

00:38:31.220 --> 00:38:34.660
sometimes they're funnier
than some of the episodes

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:37.510
because we had a lot of fun.

00:38:37.510 --> 00:38:41.400
And we still have a
lot of fun on this show

00:38:41.400 --> 00:38:43.920
but it is an
entirely different--

00:38:43.920 --> 00:38:47.170
it takes 14 hours to
shoot it in a day,

00:38:47.170 --> 00:38:50.329
and it's not as funny a subject.

00:38:50.329 --> 00:38:51.120
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:38:51.120 --> 00:38:52.390
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:52.390 --> 00:38:55.130
ALAN SEALES: So how did
you get your start, though?

00:38:55.130 --> 00:38:57.865
So you started out doing
theater in high school?

00:38:57.865 --> 00:38:58.740
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah.

00:38:58.740 --> 00:39:00.839
I did a play in first grade.

00:39:00.839 --> 00:39:01.880
It kept going from there.

00:39:01.880 --> 00:39:02.796
It was always theatre.

00:39:02.796 --> 00:39:05.190
I didn't do, like,
commercials or anything.

00:39:05.190 --> 00:39:07.810
I went to high school
with Mike Myers

00:39:07.810 --> 00:39:09.130
on the south side of Toronto.

00:39:09.130 --> 00:39:09.330
ALAN SEALES: He's Canadian.

00:39:09.330 --> 00:39:09.790
Yeah.

00:39:09.790 --> 00:39:11.190
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah so we
knew each other a little bit.

00:39:11.190 --> 00:39:13.480
But he was already in
Canadian television

00:39:13.480 --> 00:39:14.990
when he was like nine, ten.

00:39:14.990 --> 00:39:16.940
And then he was doing
commercials and episodes

00:39:16.940 --> 00:39:18.370
of things.

00:39:18.370 --> 00:39:23.650
But I was strictly just theatre
at school and competitions--

00:39:23.650 --> 00:39:25.480
you know, skit
competitions and stuff.

00:39:25.480 --> 00:39:28.125
But 11th grade is
when it sort of-- I

00:39:28.125 --> 00:39:31.224
did a production of "Godspell,"
and that was, you know.

00:39:31.224 --> 00:39:32.890
ALAN SEALES: Who were
you in "Godspell"?

00:39:32.890 --> 00:39:33.848
ERIC MCCORMACK: Christ.

00:39:37.800 --> 00:39:41.130
As I affectionately
call him, Christ.

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:44.194
That changed everything because
it's kind of a rock musical,

00:39:44.194 --> 00:39:46.360
compared to-- we had been
doing "Annie Get Your Gun"

00:39:46.360 --> 00:39:47.265
and all of those
old-fashioned things.

00:39:47.265 --> 00:39:49.499
And all of a sudden, to
have my peers, who had never

00:39:49.499 --> 00:39:51.790
really accepted me-- I was
not an athlete or anything--

00:39:51.790 --> 00:39:54.740
suddenly, like, forced
to watch one of the songs

00:39:54.740 --> 00:39:57.347
at an assembly, you know,
and at the end of it,

00:39:57.347 --> 00:39:58.930
they jumped on their
feet and cheered.

00:39:58.930 --> 00:40:00.985
It was like, OK, I can do this.

00:40:00.985 --> 00:40:02.110
This I can do for a living.

00:40:02.110 --> 00:40:02.830
ALAN SEALES: So you sing.

00:40:02.830 --> 00:40:03.280
ERIC MCCORMACK: I sing.

00:40:03.280 --> 00:40:04.076
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, of
course, because you

00:40:04.076 --> 00:40:05.440
were in "Music Man" and
everything, as well.

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:06.020
Yes.

00:40:06.020 --> 00:40:09.890
So you just did a
concert-- what was this?

00:40:09.890 --> 00:40:11.662
A year or two ago?

00:40:11.662 --> 00:40:13.120
ERIC MCCORMACK: I
did a show that I

00:40:13.120 --> 00:40:16.360
had been sort of creating
in my brain for 30 years.

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:20.100
It was called "The Concert I
Never Gave-- except for, like,

00:40:20.100 --> 00:40:22.820
2000 times in my
bedroom" because I did.

00:40:22.820 --> 00:40:24.132
I was that guy, at 16.

00:40:24.132 --> 00:40:25.590
When other people
were doing things

00:40:25.590 --> 00:40:29.760
like dating and drinking,
I was in my bedroom

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:32.500
dressing up like Alice
Cooper and Freddie Mercury

00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:34.870
and wishing that I
could be a rock star.

00:40:34.870 --> 00:40:37.480
So I really wanted
to be an actor.

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:38.164
And I got to be.

00:40:38.164 --> 00:40:39.580
So that was no
longer the fantasy.

00:40:39.580 --> 00:40:42.560
The fantasy, to this day,
is still rock and roll.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:45.100
So I did this show where I sang.

00:40:45.100 --> 00:40:48.370
It was myself and my piano
player who is a friend of mine.

00:40:48.370 --> 00:40:50.010
He's the keyboard
player for The Who.

00:40:50.010 --> 00:40:52.117
So already, there's kind
of a fantasy level there.

00:40:52.117 --> 00:40:53.200
He put together this band.

00:40:53.200 --> 00:40:57.867
And I sang-- it was mostly songs
by popular artists but not.

00:40:57.867 --> 00:40:59.450
The songs themselves
were like B-sides

00:40:59.450 --> 00:41:01.220
and, like, you know,
the last song on side

00:41:01.220 --> 00:41:04.420
three of some album that--
but they were my favorites

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:05.470
when I was 16.

00:41:05.470 --> 00:41:07.040
And I had stories behind them.

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:09.761
And when Elton John
did "Will and Grace,"

00:41:09.761 --> 00:41:11.010
there was a story behind that.

00:41:11.010 --> 00:41:11.730
So I'd tell that story.

00:41:11.730 --> 00:41:13.350
Then I did this rare
Elton John song.

00:41:13.350 --> 00:41:13.635
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:41:13.635 --> 00:41:14.490
Right.

00:41:14.490 --> 00:41:16.915
I feel like doing a
sitcom-- this kind of plays

00:41:16.915 --> 00:41:18.790
on her question a little
bit-- doing a sitcom

00:41:18.790 --> 00:41:23.030
would be more enjoyable for you
in that it is more theatresque.

00:41:23.030 --> 00:41:23.530
Right?

00:41:23.530 --> 00:41:25.160
Because you're in front
of a live audience.

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:26.445
You only do a couple takes.

00:41:26.445 --> 00:41:26.740
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah.

00:41:26.740 --> 00:41:29.031
ALAN SEALES: I mean, in a
theatre, you have no retakes.

00:41:29.031 --> 00:41:30.780
ERIC MCCORMACK: Exactly.

00:41:30.780 --> 00:41:32.770
And as you were
pointing out, twice,

00:41:32.770 --> 00:41:34.489
we did actually
live episodes, like,

00:41:34.489 --> 00:41:36.530
as America was watching
them, we were doing them.

00:41:36.530 --> 00:41:38.696
And those were-- they didn't
look as good because it

00:41:38.696 --> 00:41:41.599
was videotaped, but
it was tremendous fun.

00:41:41.599 --> 00:41:42.390
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:41:42.390 --> 00:41:43.450
Well, do you prefer that?

00:41:43.450 --> 00:41:45.694
Do you prefer the live
aspect, versus [INAUDIBLE]?

00:41:45.694 --> 00:41:46.860
ERIC MCCORMACK: I really do.

00:41:46.860 --> 00:41:49.510
I mean, I'll always do back to
the theatre because I do love

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:50.010
that a lot.

00:41:50.010 --> 00:41:52.240
And a show like this
takes it out of you

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:55.350
because it's-- anyone that
does an hour drama, I mean,

00:41:55.350 --> 00:41:56.710
it's non-stop.

00:41:56.710 --> 00:41:57.630
It's just--

00:41:57.630 --> 00:41:58.830
ALAN SEALES: Do you
do an episode a week?

00:41:58.830 --> 00:41:59.670
Is that a typical schedule?

00:41:59.670 --> 00:42:00.530
ERIC MCCORMACK: It's
a seven day schedule.

00:42:00.530 --> 00:42:01.640
But, you know, we
have weekends off.

00:42:01.640 --> 00:42:02.140
So yeah.

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:03.400
But it's seven days.

00:42:03.400 --> 00:42:03.950
ALAN SEALES: So for how long?

00:42:03.950 --> 00:42:05.110
You film for three months?

00:42:05.110 --> 00:42:06.300
ERIC MCCORMACK: January to June.

00:42:06.300 --> 00:42:07.360
We're finished next week.

00:42:07.360 --> 00:42:08.120
ALAN SEALES: Oh, wow,
because you're still

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:08.660
filming the finale?

00:42:08.660 --> 00:42:08.920
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah.

00:42:08.920 --> 00:42:10.339
I go back and shoot tomorrow.

00:42:10.339 --> 00:42:11.380
ALAN SEALES: Well, sorry.

00:42:11.380 --> 00:42:12.570
ERIC MCCORMACK: Now is
the time when I'm happy.

00:42:12.570 --> 00:42:14.194
No, because we premiere
tomorrow night,

00:42:14.194 --> 00:42:16.030
and it's so great
to get the word out.

00:42:18.474 --> 00:42:20.640
As I was saying before,
it's a smaller universe now,

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:23.214
but you still--
it puts everything

00:42:23.214 --> 00:42:24.630
you have into
something like this.

00:42:24.630 --> 00:42:27.070
And you just want people to
see it, and you want to--

00:42:27.070 --> 00:42:28.210
ALAN SEALES: Well, speaking
of getting the word out,

00:42:28.210 --> 00:42:30.460
you have a Twitter account
that you want to plug here?

00:42:30.460 --> 00:42:32.070
ERIC MCCORMACK:
It's @EricMcCormack.

00:42:32.070 --> 00:42:34.810
And yes, please.

00:42:34.810 --> 00:42:37.090
I've got 70,000 loyal followers.

00:42:37.090 --> 00:42:38.259
And I want more.

00:42:38.259 --> 00:42:40.050
ALAN SEALES: Oh, we
had a question jump up.

00:42:40.050 --> 00:42:40.370
Yeah?

00:42:40.370 --> 00:42:40.690
ERIC MCCORMACK: Hello.

00:42:40.690 --> 00:42:41.231
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:42:41.231 --> 00:42:43.200
So I'm a really big TV fan.

00:42:43.200 --> 00:42:44.750
So I watch a lot
of different shows.

00:42:44.750 --> 00:42:46.430
And "Will and Grace" is
one of the earlier ones

00:42:46.430 --> 00:42:48.300
that I watched when I started,
about six years ago, just

00:42:48.300 --> 00:42:50.130
watching all of the
seasons that I could.

00:42:50.130 --> 00:42:53.090
And the Emmys have changed a
lot since you and your show

00:42:53.090 --> 00:42:55.167
have been nominated
and won and everything.

00:42:55.167 --> 00:42:57.500
And I was wondering what you
think about the Emmys today

00:42:57.500 --> 00:42:59.970
and how television has kind
of changed since you've

00:42:59.970 --> 00:43:02.660
kind of done sitcoms,
versus now, doing a drama.

00:43:02.660 --> 00:43:06.150
ERIC MCCORMACK: Well, you know,
Jim Parsons, from, I think

00:43:06.150 --> 00:43:07.770
"Big Bang Theory"
is the closest thing

00:43:07.770 --> 00:43:10.400
to what we used to do
that is on television now.

00:43:10.400 --> 00:43:11.380
And he's brilliant.

00:43:11.380 --> 00:43:13.250
And so when I see
that kind of show win,

00:43:13.250 --> 00:43:14.980
I go, well, not that
much has changed.

00:43:14.980 --> 00:43:17.850
But certainly, in terms of
drama and what cable is doing,

00:43:17.850 --> 00:43:19.680
it's changed entirely.

00:43:19.680 --> 00:43:21.560
I mean, I think almost
everything nominated

00:43:21.560 --> 00:43:25.260
this year was not from
a network, you know?

00:43:25.260 --> 00:43:28.050
But I think that's OK.

00:43:28.050 --> 00:43:31.695
That old the way has to go.

00:43:31.695 --> 00:43:33.820
It benefited those of us
that were on popular shows

00:43:33.820 --> 00:43:35.403
because we got a big
number of people.

00:43:35.403 --> 00:43:36.580
It was less to choose from.

00:43:36.580 --> 00:43:39.250
But those days are gone.

00:43:39.250 --> 00:43:44.600
I mean, everyone in this
generation, with Google

00:43:44.600 --> 00:43:46.927
and everything else, we can
choose whatever we want.

00:43:46.927 --> 00:43:48.260
ALAN SEALES: On your cell phone?

00:43:48.260 --> 00:43:49.968
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah,
on your cell phone.

00:43:49.968 --> 00:43:52.070
So the Emmys are, in
and of themselves,

00:43:52.070 --> 00:43:55.600
going to become less
representational of what's

00:43:55.600 --> 00:43:57.670
really out there.

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:01.720
I think nowadays, if I
were on a great cable show,

00:44:01.720 --> 00:44:03.820
doing great work, and
still not nominated,

00:44:03.820 --> 00:44:05.780
I wouldn't take it
all that personally.

00:44:05.780 --> 00:44:09.210
I mean, there's just too much
good stuff to choose from.

00:44:09.210 --> 00:44:11.790
So I don't know.

00:44:11.790 --> 00:44:12.767
That could change.

00:44:12.767 --> 00:44:14.850
There's still only ever
going to be five nominees.

00:44:14.850 --> 00:44:17.750
And they will not
necessarily represent

00:44:17.750 --> 00:44:18.792
what everyone's watching.

00:44:18.792 --> 00:44:20.333
AUDIENCE: They
actually recently said

00:44:20.333 --> 00:44:22.940
that they might consider doing
a best show, which combines

00:44:22.940 --> 00:44:25.965
both the best series categories
together, because there

00:44:25.965 --> 00:44:26.947
have been changes.

00:44:26.947 --> 00:44:28.280
What would you think about that?

00:44:28.280 --> 00:44:30.110
ERIC MCCORMACK: What
do you mean best show?

00:44:30.110 --> 00:44:33.210
AUDIENCE: Instead of best
comedy series, best drama,

00:44:33.210 --> 00:44:35.260
they would combine it into 10.

00:44:35.260 --> 00:44:37.274
How do you think that would--

00:44:37.274 --> 00:44:38.690
ERIC MCCORMACK: I
find that weird.

00:44:38.690 --> 00:44:40.620
AUDIENCE: It was a weird
little theory that people had,

00:44:40.620 --> 00:44:41.386
out there.

00:44:41.386 --> 00:44:42.260
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah.

00:44:42.260 --> 00:44:43.340
I find that strange.

00:44:43.340 --> 00:44:45.840
ALAN SEALES: Oh, is this the
Emmy fan of [INAUDIBLE] rumors?

00:44:48.510 --> 00:44:51.570
ERIC MCCORMACK: Yeah, because
I think comedy and a drama

00:44:51.570 --> 00:44:52.880
are very different animals.

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:54.704
You know?

00:44:54.704 --> 00:44:56.792
You know what's very strange?

00:44:56.792 --> 00:44:59.130
It was the Golden
Globes or something.

00:44:59.130 --> 00:45:01.870
"Will and Grace" has
the record for the most

00:45:01.870 --> 00:45:04.946
Golden Globe nominations
with no wins at all.

00:45:04.946 --> 00:45:05.720
It's true.

00:45:05.720 --> 00:45:06.220
Look it up.

00:45:06.220 --> 00:45:08.630
25 nominations, and
none of us ever won.

00:45:08.630 --> 00:45:10.560
And every year, we'd
go get the same table.

00:45:10.560 --> 00:45:14.730
And Max, who created the show,
every time somebody wouldn't

00:45:14.730 --> 00:45:19.035
win, he would grab his
glass, and we'd all go, yeah!

00:45:19.035 --> 00:45:20.110
And we'd cheer.

00:45:20.110 --> 00:45:23.310
And so the cameras would always
come to us like we'd won.

00:45:23.310 --> 00:45:24.000
But we hadn't.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:26.860
Some other guy was walking
up and taking the thing.

00:45:26.860 --> 00:45:32.110
But I think it was at the
Globes that the category

00:45:32.110 --> 00:45:34.460
for Supporting Actor
is for everything.

00:45:34.460 --> 00:45:36.720
Best Supporting Actor
on any television

00:45:36.720 --> 00:45:38.320
show-- drama, miniseries.

00:45:38.320 --> 00:45:41.090
So Sean always managed to
get nominated [INAUDIBLE],

00:45:41.090 --> 00:45:43.850
but always with this pool
of, like, opposite Vanessa

00:45:43.850 --> 00:45:45.120
Redgrave or something.

00:45:45.120 --> 00:45:46.140
It was just madness.

00:45:46.140 --> 00:45:48.640
So when you start to
make it too small,

00:45:48.640 --> 00:45:51.500
the award starts to have
less-- I mean, for me,

00:45:51.500 --> 00:45:54.760
it meant so much because the
big show, for me, growing up,

00:45:54.760 --> 00:45:56.339
was "Get Smart" which was--

00:45:56.339 --> 00:45:57.130
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:45:57.130 --> 00:45:59.088
ERIC MCCORMACK: I didn't
see it's original run,

00:45:59.088 --> 00:46:00.940
but I saw reruns in the '70s.

00:46:00.940 --> 00:46:03.430
And Don Adams won that award.

00:46:03.430 --> 00:46:04.060
You know?

00:46:04.060 --> 00:46:05.549
Actually, there's
a famous story--

00:46:05.549 --> 00:46:08.090
I don't know if it's apocryphal
that on Emmy night, you know,

00:46:08.090 --> 00:46:11.664
the Emmys have the wings
that are really sharp.

00:46:11.664 --> 00:46:13.080
And apparently,
he and Don Rickles

00:46:13.080 --> 00:46:17.660
got so drunk that Don Adams
fell asleep on his Emmy

00:46:17.660 --> 00:46:20.494
and punctured his throat and
was bleeding all over his tux.

00:46:20.494 --> 00:46:21.660
I don't know if that's true.

00:46:21.660 --> 00:46:22.576
But I love that story.

00:46:22.576 --> 00:46:24.289
But just the fact that--

00:46:24.289 --> 00:46:26.330
